 There are **three bugs** here. Let me walk through each one:

---

**Bug 1 — `cleanData` filter never actually filters**

```js
$: cleanData = data.filter(d => {
  const x = +d.properties?.[varX];
  const y = +d.properties?.[varY];
  // ← no return statement! always returns undefined (falsy) → empty array
});
```

Fix:
```js
$: cleanData = data.filter(d => {
  const x = +d.properties?.[varX];
  const y = +d.properties?.[varY];
  return !isNaN(x) && !isNaN(y); // ← actually return the condition
});
```

---

**Bug 2 — brush is set up in `onMount` but `cleanData` is empty at that point**

The brush references `cleanData` and `xScale`/`yScale` in its callback, but those are captured at mount time when data hasn't loaded yet. The brush itself is fine to set up once, but the callback needs to read the *current* values of `cleanData` and the scales. Since these are module-level `$:` variables, the callback will actually close over the reactive variables correctly — **but** the bigger issue is that `d3.select(svg).append("g")` runs once and the brush `<g>` is appended to the SVG outside of Svelte's control. This is fine, but make sure the brush layer is appended **after** the circles by moving it to the end, or it'll block mouse events. Use a dedicated bound `<g>` element instead:

```svelte
<!-- in template, AFTER the circles -->
<g bind:this={brushGroup}></g>
```

```js
let brushGroup;
onMount(() => {
  const brush = d3.brush()
    .extent([[margin.left, margin.top], [width - margin.right, height - margin.bottom]])
    .on("end", (event) => {
      const sel = event.selection;
      if (!sel) { setSelected([]); return; }
      const [[x0, y0], [x1, y1]] = sel;
      const brushed = cleanData.filter(d => {
        const x = xScale(+d.properties[varX]);
        const y = yScale(+d.properties[varY]);
        return x >= x0 && x <= x1 && y >= y0 && y <= y1;
      });
      setSelected(brushed);
    });

  d3.select(brushGroup).call(brush);
});
```

---

**Bug 3 — `selected.includes(d)` will never match**

`selected` is an array of GeoJSON feature objects set by the brush. But `.includes()` checks reference equality — the brushed objects and the `cleanData` objects are the same references, so this *should* work. However, you're also receiving `selectedPoints` as a separate prop (from the map selection) but not using it in the fill. Decide which one drives the highlight and use it consistently. If you want both to highlight, merge them:

```js
$: highlightSet = new Set([
  ...(selected || []).map(d => d.properties.country),
  ...(selectedPoints || []).map(d => d.properties.country)
]);
```

Then in the template:
```svelte
fill={highlightSet.has(d.properties.country) ? "orange" : "steelblue"}
```

