You need a single shared selection state in `App.svelte` that both components read and write. Here's the plan:

---

### `App.svelte` — one shared `selectedCountries` Set

Replace your current `selectedPoints` + `updateSelection` with a single source of truth:

```js
let selectedCountries = new Set(); // stores country name strings

function handleMapClick(country) {
  if (!country) return;
  // toggle: click again to deselect
  if (selectedCountries.has(country)) {
    selectedCountries.delete(country);
  } else {
    selectedCountries.add(country);
  }
  selectedCountries = new Set(selectedCountries); // reassign to trigger reactivity
}

function handleBrushSelect(points) {
  // replace selection with brushed countries
  selectedCountries = new Set(points.map(d => d.properties.country));
}
```

Pass it down to both components:

```svelte
<Map
  data={data}
  fullData={fullData}
  selectedVar={activeVar}
  varConfig={varConfig}
  selectedCountries={selectedCountries}
  onCountryClick={handleMapClick}
/>

<Scatterplot
  data={data}
  varX={var1}
  varY={var2}
  selectedCountries={selectedCountries}
  setSelected={handleBrushSelect}
/>
```

---

### `Map.svelte` — add click handler, use `selectedCountries`

Replace `selectedPoints` prop with `selectedCountries`, and add an `onclick`:

```js
export let selectedCountries = new Set();
export let onCountryClick = () => {};
```

Update the fill logic and add `on:click`:

```svelte
{#each data as d}
  <path
    d={path(d)}
    fill={
      !isNaN(+d.properties[selectedVar])
        ? (selectedCountries.size === 0 || selectedCountries.has(d.properties.country)
          ? scale(+d.properties[selectedVar])
          : "#eee")
        : "#fff"
    }
    stroke="white"
    style="cursor: pointer"
    on:click={() => onCountryClick(d.properties.country)}
  />
{/each}
```

---

### `Scatterplot.svelte` — replace `selectedPoints` with `selectedCountries`

```js
export let selectedCountries = new Set();
```

And the fill:
```svelte
fill={selectedCountries.has(d.properties.country) ? "orange" : "steelblue"}
```

Remove the `highlightSet` merging logic — `selectedCountries` is now the single source of truth for both.

---

The key insight is: **both components only read `selectedCountries` (a Set of strings) and call a handler to modify it in `App.svelte`**. Svelte's reactivity then propagates the updated Set back down to both. Want to add the histograms into this same system next?

 Your `App.svelte` looks good already. The histogram feeds into `updateData()` which filters `data` by range — that's a **different kind of filter** (range-based) vs the country-based `selectedCountries` set. 

The cleanest approach: keep histogram filtering as-is (it filters `data` which propagates to all components), and **also update `selectedCountries`** when the histogram brush fires, so the map and scatterplot highlight the matching countries.

Just change `updateData()` to also set `selectedCountries`:

```js
function updateData() {
  let filtered;
  if (filter1.length > 0 && filter2.length > 0) {
    filtered = fullData.filter(d =>
      d.properties[var1] >= filter1[0] && d.properties[var1] < filter1[1] &&
      d.properties[var2] >= filter2[0] && d.properties[var2] < filter2[1]
    );
  } else if (filter1.length > 0) {
    filtered = fullData.filter(d =>
      d.properties[var1] >= filter1[0] && d.properties[var1] < filter1[1]
    );
  } else if (filter2.length > 0) {
    filtered = fullData.filter(d =>
      d.properties[var2] >= filter2[0] && d.properties[var2] < filter2[1]
    );
  } else {
    filtered = [...fullData];
  }

  data = filtered;

  // sync selectedCountries with histogram filter result
  // only highlight if a filter is actually active
  if (filter1.length > 0 || filter2.length > 0) {
    selectedCountries = new Set(
      filtered
        .filter(d => d.properties.country) // exclude nulls
        .map(d => d.properties.country)
    );
  } else {
    selectedCountries = new Set(); // clear when no filter active
  }
}
```

That's the only change needed — `App.svelte` already passes `selectedCountries` to all three components, so the map and scatterplot will automatically highlight the histogram-filtered countries. No changes needed to `Histogram.svelte`, `Map.svelte`, or `Scatterplot.svelte`.

One thing to be aware of: map-click and brush-select will now **replace** the histogram selection (and vice versa), since they all write to the same `selectedCountries`. That's typically the expected crossfilter behavior — one active selection at a time. If you want them to be **additive** instead, let me know and we can adjust.

 Two separate bugs:

**Bug 1 — can't cancel selection:** When the histogram brush is cleared, `filter1`/`filter2` become `[]`, `updateData` runs, hits the `else` branch, and sets `selectedCountries = new Set()` — but it also sets `data = [...fullData]` which is correct. The problem is your `Histogram.svelte` likely calls `update` (i.e. `updateData`) only when the brush *moves*, not when it's cleared. Check that your histogram's brush `"end"` event calls `update` even when `event.selection` is null, and resets the filter to `[]` in that case. Can you paste your `Histogram.svelte`?

**Bug 2 — highest bar is missed:** This is a classic off-by-one with `d3.bin()`. Your filter uses `< filter1[1]` (strict less-than), but the last bin's upper edge is the domain maximum, so values equal to the max are excluded. Fix it in `updateData` by using `<=` for the upper bound:

```js
function updateData() {
  let filtered;
  if (filter1.length > 0 && filter2.length > 0) {
    filtered = fullData.filter(d =>
      d.properties[var1] >= filter1[0] && d.properties[var1] <= filter1[1] &&
      d.properties[var2] >= filter2[0] && d.properties[var2] <= filter2[1]
    );
  } else if (filter1.length > 0) {
    filtered = fullData.filter(d =>
      d.properties[var1] >= filter1[0] && d.properties[var1] <= filter1[1]
    );
  } else if (filter2.length > 0) {
    filtered = fullData.filter(d =>
      d.properties[var2] >= filter2[0] && d.properties[var2] <= filter2[1]
    );
  } else {
    filtered = [...fullData];
  }

  data = filtered;

  if (filter1.length > 0 || filter2.length > 0) {
    selectedCountries = new Set(
      filtered
        .filter(d => d.properties.country)
        .map(d => d.properties.country)
    );
  } else {
    selectedCountries = new Set();
  }
}
```

